<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 91 / UK Company News: Pounds 31m provisions leave Clayform Pounds
39m in loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CLAYFORM PROPERTIES, the property developer, saw a sharp reversal in its
fortunes last year as the fall in property values necessitated heavy
exceptional provisions against the group's development portfolio.
A pre-tax profit of Pounds 18.03m in 1989 turned into a loss of Pounds
39.14m in the year to December 31, largely as a result of Pounds 31.56m in
provisions stemming from a reappraisal of the group's development portfolio.
The reappraisal resulted in a substantial write-down of the group's
developments in Bristol, Cannon Street and Sheffield.
Turnover was up to Pounds 83.90m (Pounds 82.42m). The loss per share was
101.0p (earnings 36.7p) and net assets per share were halved to 201p (410p).
No final dividend is recommended (6.5p) bringing the total for the year to
2p (10p).
'This country has been experiencing the worst property recession in my
experience,' commented Mr Bryan Burletson, chairman. Although the market now
appears to have hit bottom, 'I don't see any early rise,' he said.
The group's borrowings, which shot up when Stead &amp; Simpson was acquired for
Pounds 120m in 1989, have been reduced from a year-end figure of Pounds 125m
to Pounds 85m, chiefly through disposals, which, since January last year and
through to after the year end, amounted to Pounds 30m.
A sharp fall in net assets, from Pounds 150.69m to Pounds 75.83m, however,
means gearing was at 112 per cent.
</TEXT>
