<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 91 / Revival of flexible work plan runs risk of Tube strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON UNDERGROUND is to revive an attempt to introduce more flexible
working practices which it modified two years ago because of a one-day
strike campaign. The move is expected later this year in spite of a current
dispute over job cuts.
London Underground proposals include allowing its 22,000 station staff to
sell tickets as well as supervising platforms, and would include a new
multi-skilled senior grade of station employee.
The corporation wants to have the flexibility when rostered staff are absent
for employees who operate as 'relief' workers to substitute for all grades
of platform staff rather than only for their own grade.
The plans are being considered amid a dispute over the corporation's attempt
to cut 1,005 jobs because of financial difficulties.
The RMT rail union is expected to announce today that members have voted for
industrial action. Members of the TSSA white collar union have already voted
for strikes by a 575 to 289 majority.
London Underground has already drawn up plans to suspend any workers who
take part in industrial action over the job cuts.
Mr Roger Straker, London Underground personnel director, said it would
negotiate further over job cuts, but if there were strikes the corporation
would 'take a very hard line indeed'.
Background, Page 9
