<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 91 / Finance &amp; The Family: Capital Gains Tax and you
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INLAND Revenue has now published its March indexation table for those
wishing to calculate their capital gains tax liability.
The table shows the allowance which investors can make for inflation on
assets sold in March. To calculate your liability, multiply the original
cost of your shares by the figure shown for the month in which you bought
them. Then subtract that indexed sum from the amount you received when you
sold the shares.
For example, supposing you bought shares for Pounds 5,000 in March 1983,
which are worth Pounds 12,000 now. Without indexation, your gain would be
Pounds 7,000, above the 1990-91 capital gains tax allowance of Pounds 5,000
(the 1991-92 allowance has been increased to Pounds 5,500).
However using the table, you multiply Pounds 5,000 by the March 1983 figure
of 1.581 to reach Pounds 7,905. Your indexed gain is just Pounds 4,095
(Pounds 12,000 minus Pounds 7,905), well below the CGT allowance.
