<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 91 / London Stock Exchange: Property sector lower
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Land Securities led most of the property sector lower after pessimistic
forecasts on property prices were published by Richard Ellis, the chartered
surveyor, and as BZW told clients to switch out of many sector leaders.
Richard Ellis forecast that for the 12 months to the end of January 1992,
the index of all property prices would fall 12 per cent. Offices would be
the hardest hit, down 22 per cent, and shops, 5 per cent lower, would be
least troubled. Rents would also suffer across the board.
BZW said investors should avoid companies heavily exposed to office
property. As well as Land Securities, down 14 to 515p, the broker identified
MEPC, 8 off at 524p, Greycoat, 2 easier at 338p and Great Portland Estates,
6 lower at 220p.
Trafalgar firm
Trafalgar House stood out among the FT-SE stocks, being bought ahead of the
interim results, due on May 8. One brokerage was a keen buyer earlier in the
week after upgrading the stock and was joined yesterday by another equally
determined house. Both were believed to be assuming that payment of the 8.8p
per share interim dividend would be maintained, leaving the stock on a
generous yield.
There was also talk of attractive break-up values if the group did decide to
hive off two of its three main trading divisions. These consist of property
investment, construction and engineering, and shipping and hotels. Against
the wider market, the shares rose 8 to 254p on turnover of 3.6m.
Composites lower
Composite insurers were weaker after a securities house lowered its profits
forecasts for most of the big stocks in the sector. Increased competition
among composites has gradually eroded profitability. The effect of this
started to be felt in first quarter and by the year end County NatWest is
forecasting that some of the leaders will report losses.
County has cut its 1991 forecast for Commercial Union to zero from a
previous estimate of a Pounds 50m profit; a loss of Pounds 95m against no
profits is expected by General Accident; while Royal Insurance is forecast
to make a Pounds 90m loss against Pounds 25m previously. CU closed 9 lower
at 499p, General Accident eased 5 to 519p and Royal Insurance slipped 10 to
432p.
McAlpine cash call
Another rights issue found the building sector distinctly edgy. The deluge
of cash calls, 16 so far this year, continued when Alfred McAlpine called
for Pounds 38.8m to reduce borrowings of around Pounds 80m.
The shares dipped amid claims that the proposed funding was 'a mercy call'
but Mr Graeme Odgers, recently-appointed chief executive, denied this,
saying 'there is too much money going out of the group by way of interest
payments'.
Analysts tended to agree with both his views and strategy, They stressed,
however, the benefits were not going to come through quickly and thought the
shares in the meantime could be caught up in the sector's weakness. They
fell 28 yesterday to 258p.
The rights issue will strengthen McAlpine's ties with Lyonnaise des
Eaux-Dumez. The French group is buying some of the rights entitlement of the
McAlpine Family Trusts and will emerge with a shareholding of 12 per cent.
BTR bucked the market trend with a rise of 3 to 384p. Smith New Court
recommended the stock, saying that the company's good margins at the bottom
of the recession bode well for profits in any recovery.
There was no stopping Maxwell Communication, up 10 to 237p. US securities
house Goldman Sachs remained a determined buyer of the stock in spite of a
profits warning from the company during the week.
The Water Package bounced as Smith New Court said the recent fall was
overdone. 'Even a disastrous result for the government in next week's local
elections is in the price,' said Mr Steven Doe at Smith. The Labour Party
has said it would renationalise the water companies, although Mr Doe belives
that such would be the regulatory controls on other privatised industries
that water would not have a singularly high political risk. The package was
more than Pounds 100 better at one point and ended at Pounds 2955, up Pounds
85 on the day.
Individual water stocks followed suit. The best performer was Thames, 8
higher at 306p.
In a quiet oil and gas sector, the only busy trading was in British Gas. The
shares eased 3 1/2 to 244 1/2 p as 7m changed hands. Analysts are to attend
a presentation on Monday to hear the long-awaited results of a review of
British Gas pricing by the government regulatory body Ofgas.
The talk yesterday was that the new formula would specify that price rises
should be kept to Retail Prices Index minus 5, compared with the current
figure of RPI-2. There could also be firmer controls over how much British
Gas could pass on higher gas costs to customers. 'This would be a tighter
regime than expected,' said Mr Steve Turner of Smith New Court.
Volume in diversified engineer Dowty rose to an unusually high 3.3m shares.
SG Warburg was a persistent bidder of the stock. The price ended unchanged
at 184p.
Guinness Mahon, the merchant bank in which the Bank of Yokohama has a 65 per
cent stake, was unchanged at 45p after it made a Pounds 49.3m rights issue.
A cash call had been anticipated. The market was not troubled by the
announcement of a Pounds 35m interim loss against a profit of Pounds 2m last
time. The shares were buoyed by the Bank of Yokohama's decision to supply a
Pounds 30m bridging loan to strengthen its capital base.
National Home Loans weakened following a fall in interim profits to Pounds
10.1m from Pounds 15.6m last time and on the announcement that it had made a
provision of Pounds 3.5m in its accounts against allegedly fraudulent
activity at one of its consumer finance subsidiaries. The shares were 5
lower at 129p but a positive statement from Mr John Darby, the chairman,
pushed NHL back to 133p, down a penny on the day.
British Airways rose 4 to 168p as 3.2m changed hands on US buying following
the recent rally in North American airline stocks. Anecdotal evidence of
increased passenger demand also buoyed the shares.
Albert Fisher added 4 at 121p after a series of presentations to Scottish
institutions.
Funding worries again beset ECC, the industrials materials group. Despite
the assurances given earlier this week that a rights issue was not a
consideration, the stock closed 8 down at 412p.
Y J Lovell was subdued by advice not to take up the new nil-paid shares
resulting from the rights issue. BZW told clients the cash call coupled with
a second batch of above and below the line write-offs in property and
waterside residential developments within the past 10 months was certainly
asking a lot of Lovell's already long-suffering shareholders. The shares
made no attempt to regain Thursday's sharp fall and closed easier at 143p,
for a two-day loss of 35.
John Mowlem was quoted ex the rights issue at 280p with the new nil-paid
shares at 16p premium, after having opened at 28p premium. Graham Wood
dipped 12 to 90p as the market became unreceptive to small sales.
A sell recommendation in a weekly investment magazine left property and
motor distribution company Wyndham 11 down at 7p.
