<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 91 / International Company News: Harcourt Brace bid abandoned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Cinema, the holding company whose interests include retailing and
entertainment, has terminated its tender offer for the publicly-held debt of
Harcourt Brace Jovanovich, the troubled US publishing and insurance group.
It seems unlikely the Dollars 1.4bn bid by General Cinema for Harcourt will
now proceed. Harcourt Brace junk bonds fell on Wall Street after the
announcement, while the shares slipped Dollars  1/16 to Dollars .
The offer was conditional on a successful tender offer by the bidder for at
least 90 per cent of the five outstanding public debt issues. but despite
several months of negotiations with bondholders, no agreement between
General Cinema and the investors over the terms proved possible.
The Massachusetts-based General Cinema has walked away from deals in the
past - it last year dropped an offer to buy in a minority stake in Neiman
Marcus, the US retailer, after stockholder resistance to the terms - and
said yesterday that it was 'moving on to other acquisition possibilities'.
Harcourt Brace, meanwhile, said it 'must now consider all its available
alternatives'.
The company made a net loss of Dollars 80.9m in 1990.
</TEXT>
