<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 91 / The Blue Arrow Trial: County stake shocked managers, jury
told
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR managers at County NatWest reacted with shock and anger when they
first learned of the size of the bank's holding in Blue Arrow and the
resultant loss after the 1987 stock market crash, an Old Bailey jury heard
yesterday.
Mr John Owen, treasurer of NatWest Investment Bank, told the court he
attended a management meeting on December 17 held before County announced
that it owned a disclosable 9.5 per cent stake in Blue Arrow which led to a
loss of Pounds 49m.
The general reaction to the draft announcement being discussed was shock and
anger, he told Mr Nicholas Purnell QC, prosecuting.
'Shock at the extent of the losses and the implications for the firm as a
whole. Anger at the lack of general notice that many people felt they had
had. 'It had clearly been unexpected to some. The scale of the losses in
particular and the residual shareholding was much larger than many realised,
he said.'
Ms Christine Downton, the chief executive of County NatWest Investment
Management, was very angry at the implications for the reputation of her
division, he said. He later told Mr Alun Jones, QC, for Mr Stephen Clark, a
County director and one of the defendants, it would have been 'improper' for
Ms Downton to have been told before of the holding, agreeing that that would
have breached a 'Chinese wall' within the County organisation.
Mr Owen agreed that he knew of the holdings taken by County, County NatWest
Securities and Union Bank of Switzerland, but was unaware the UBS stake was
covered by an indemnity from County.
County NatWest, NatWest Investment Bank, UBS Phillips &amp; Drew Securities and
seven individuals all deny conspiring to mislead the markets over the result
of the Pounds 837m rights issue.
After the issue, NWIB faced a total risk of almost Pounds 160m.
Mr Owen organised an options hedge to protect against a fall in the share
price. That covered Pounds 83m of the risk and realised a Pounds 90m profit,
he said.
The trial continues on Monday.
</TEXT>
