<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 91 / Sanctions warning to Japan: Construction, intellectual
property worry Washington
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bush Administration yesterday warned Japan it would impose sanctions for
its failure to open its public construction market and gave China, India and
Thailand six to nine months to improve their protection of intellectual
property before also facing trade curbs.
Mrs Carla Hills, the US trade representative, said the US would bar Japanese
companies from all federal government construction projects unless agreement
was reached in 30 days to improve access for US companies wishing to enter
the Japanese construction market.
Japanese companies have been making on average about Dollars 2.4bn (Pounds
1.4bn) a year for projects in the US market. US companies have won contracts
worth only Dollars 200m since 1988.
Mrs Hills identified China, India and Thailand under the Special 301
provision of the 1988 trade law as 'Priority Foreign Countries'. These are
countries whose failure to enforce laws protecting patents, copyrights,
trademarks or software is deemed to be 'the most onerous and egregious.'
Under Special 301, the trade representative may impose sanctions after six
to nine months of negotiations. Mrs Hills said the sanctions would be
'matched with the results' of the losses incurred by US companies.
In another action, Mrs Hills cited Norway for discrimination against US
companies in its government procurement practices.
She has requested consultations with Norway, who she said has violated the
Gatt procurement code by excluding US suppliers from the procurement of an
electronic toll collection system for the city of Trondheim.
She also cited the EC - and Germany, France and Italy separately - for
discriminatory practices in procuring heavy electrical equipment or
telecommunications equipment. She noted that US and EC negotiators recently
agreed to set December 1991 as a target date for 'substantial completion' of
an expanded Gatt Procurement Code.
Thus she will wait until January 1992 to review the European procurement
practices.
</TEXT>
