<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 91 / Reed slims stake in BSkyB venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REED INTERNATIONAL, one of the big five backers of British Sky Broadcasting,
said yesterday that it would not invest any more money in the satellite
television venture.
As a result Mr Ian Irvine, Reed deputy chief executive, resigned as both
chairman and a director of BSkyB. He will be replaced as chairman by Mr
Frank Barlow, managing director of Pearson, publishers of the Financial
Times.
The decision by Reed, which has committed more than Pounds 180m in equity,
loans and guarantees to BSkyB, was revealed to a BSkyB board meeting.
Reed's 10 per cent stake in BSkyB will now be diluted to around 4 per cent
and the company said last night it would write down at least its equity
stake in the venture - Pounds 34m net of tax.
Mr Peter Davis, Reed's chairman and chief executive, said last night he was
confident about the long-term potential for satellite television in the UK
and the viability of BSkyB. 'However, the board does not wish to increase
its investment further in BSkyB as we prefer to invest in our core
publishing and information businesses where we have more direct management
control.'
The issue came to a head over plans to raise a further Pounds 200m for the
venture following last November's merger of British Satellite Broadcasting
and Mr Rupert Murdoch's Sky Television.
The four main BSB shareholders - Granada, Pearson, publishers of the
Financial Times, Chargeurs and Reed - were expected to put up about Pounds
100m with Mr Murdoch being responsible for the other half.
The Reed board decision not to go ahead was unanimous. Granada will put up
its original share of the Pounds 100m package and Pearson and Chargeurs will
take up the slack left by Reed. The Pearson and Chargeurs stake will rise to
around 15 per cent each.
Agreement on the Pounds 200m package - Mr Murdoch will put up his share in a
mixture of cash and value such as film rights - is expected to be completed
at the beginning of next week.
Reed's decision was partly motivated by fears that the current fund-raising
of Pounds 200m might not be enough to see the venture through to
profitability.
The decision not to participate in further funding was taken in spite of the
fact that Mr Davis and Mr Irvine were instrumental in bringing BSB and Sky
together for what turned out to be successful merger talks.
In fact, Reed may have encouraged the merger in order to safeguard the
future of its Pounds 130m in guarantees and a Pounds 17m loan.
The Reed decision comes at a time when satellite dish sales are rising.
Market research carried out for Satellite TV Finance, a specialist FT
newsletter, also suggests that 54 per cent of subscribers to the old Sky
Movie channel will also buy BSB's Movie channel.
Satellite rental, Page 8
Murdoch in talks, Page 10
</TEXT>
