<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 91 / Bush to call in G7 ministers: Germany comes under renewed US
pressure to cut interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush will call finance ministers and central bank governors
at tomorrow's Group of Seven meeting in Washington into the White House to
press the case for lower interest rates.
In particular he is expected to increase pressure on Germany to cut its
rates and so help boost the world economy.
But Mr Karl Otto Pohl, the Bundesbank president, said in a speech in
Washington yesterday that German monetary policy would remain tight for the
time being to mop up excess liquidity which had been created by the economic
and monetary union of the two Germanys.
Repeated US demands for an easing of German monetary policy and the refusal
of the finance ministry in Bonn or the Bundesbank in Frankfurt to alter
their stance will make the G7 meeting difficult. If anything, the
differences on monetary policy and growth between the US and Germany have
widened in recent weeks.
In Bonn late on Thursday, Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister, said
Germany was not prepared to lower rates and added that the US should not
seek to end its recession through inflation.
At the same time, a US Treasury official in Washington said European
pre-occupations with combating inflation appeared passe in view of the
problems facing the world economy since the political liberalisation of
eastern Europe and the Gulf war.
The US believes that Europe has failed to understand the implications of a
huge demand for finance from the Soviet Middle East. In these circumstances
it is feared high real interest rates threaten the world economy and
political stability. The US wants stronger global economic growth and is
concerned that growth in Europe is slowing and that there is no clear
evidence of recovery in the US, Britain and Canada.
The US Treasury official suggested that the time may have come for the G7
countries - the US, Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada - to
shift their aims from achieving non-inflationary growth to achieving growth
with low inflation.
For its part, Germany will underline that it is performing an service for
the world economy through its financial support for the Soviet Union and
eastern Europe. Mr Waigel said in Bonn that Germany had earmarked DM25bn
(Pounds 8.3bn) for this purpose.
Mr Pohl said Germany's trading partners would benefit substantially from the
country's unification.
Strong growth in western Germany would be welcomed by countries in
recession, while a 'drastic decrease' in Germany's trade surplus provided an
important growth stimulus for Germany's trading partners, he said.
Mr Pohl said it was difficult to understand complaints that Germany was
draining global savings to finance union. Instead of blaming Germany, there
should be a sustained effort by all deficit countries to improve national
savings and bring about early implementation of agreed plans to boost the
financial resources of the International Monetary Fund.
Fall in US output, Page 2
Editorial Comment, Page 6
Money markets, Page 11
</TEXT>
