FT  27 APR 91 / Finance &amp; The Family: Directors' Transactions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS MACDONALD, Directus Ltd
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE IS little evidence of any let-up in the weight of selling by company
directors and purchasers are still few and far between.
Yet more selling in the insurance broking sector included the week's largest
single deal. Both the chairman and the chief executive of Lloyd Thompson
sold tranches of stock during the course of 1990, and chief executive Ken
Carter has just disposed of 35 per cent of his holding, realising more than
Pounds 2.2m. Like most insurance brokers, interim results revealed the
extent to which their business has remained relatively unaffected by
recession.
Shares in engineering group Metalrax remained virtually unchanged after the
sale of 1.2m shares by non-executive director Derek Coombs. The shares have
enjoyed an impressive recovery since the low point in January.
Wace Group, the pre-press services company, has seen two directors sell
580,000 shares between them, of which 100,000 were bought by another main
board director. The company has grown rapidly in a highly-fragmented
industry and directors may be reducing holdings built up after taking up
shares in last summer's rights issue.
Option related sales have been very evident, particularly among the
blue-chip stocks. Directors in Shell, Prudential Corporation, Cadbury
Schweppes and Guinness have all taken this opportunity to take profits on
their share options.
