<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / London Stock Exchange: Market support for ICI
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ICI disclosed sharply lower first-quarter results, but still at the top end
of analysts' expectations, some of whom moved quickly to upgrade their
forecasts.
All were particularly impressed with results from what were thought to be
the trouble spots: bulk chemicals and agrochemicals. One disappointing area,
again contrary to expectations, was pharmaceuticals. Analysts blamed heavy
buying of drugs in the previous quarter ahead of price rises.
The range of forecasts for the full year is still wide. BZW, not the most
pessimistic of securities houses on ICI, lifted its profits estimate by
Pounds 20m to Pounds 770m. County NatWest, which issued a buy note on the
stock on Tuesday, reiterated its position and Pounds 850m prediction. Hoare
Govett, ICI's broker, moved from 'undervalued' to 'buy'. Hoare has written
in an Pounds 875m profit for the year.
ICI rose 18 at one point but closed just 3 better on balance at 1073p.
Turnover was a solid 1.9m shares.
Assets sale stories
The oil sector was alive with speculation that the sale of Occidental's
North Sea assets had been finalised, and that Elf Aquitaine, the French
state-owned oil group and long-time favourite to gain control of the assets,
had triumphed with a Dollars 1bn-plus bid. The story focused dealers' minds
on the 25 per cent stake that Elf holds in Enterprise Oil, and which many
expect to be placed in the market.
Enterprise is also thought to have bid for the assets, along with Atlantic
Richfield, the US oil group. Specialists said the Elf stake in Enterprise
had been overhanging the market and had depressed the exploration and
production sub-sector for many months; if it is sold it will lead to an
upward rerating. Enterprise shares dipped 5 to 554p.
Reuters erratic
Reuters' annual meeting caused the company's share price to move
erratically. Early in the presentation, Reuters management said revenue
would be flat for the year. Some analysts reported this immediately to
clients and the shares dropped below Pounds 8.
The company later said 'increasing cash balances will assist us in growing
our 1991 profits'. The implication that there would therefore be an
improvement on last year's Pounds 320m, the figure that some analysts have
forecast to be repeated this year, pushed the shares back up to within a few
pence of the previous night's close.
The shares weakened again in the last hour of trade, with marketmakers
saying that a US house had been caught with an over-long position in the
stock. Reuters ended a net 20 off at 803p after exceptionally high turnover
of 4m.
Monday's earthquake in Central America sent shares in the two big banana
importers, Geest and Fyffes, higher. Geest gained 28 to 347p and Fyffes rose
2 to 93p. UK importers are expected to benefit from higher retail prices,
while Caribbean suppliers are likely to supply from stock. Geest was also
boosted following a meeting with shareholders at brokers Cazenove.
Asda firmed a penny to 122p as it began its series of meetings with
securities houses. Brokers lowered their 1991/92 forecasts following the
meetings to Pounds 197m to Pounds 215m from Pounds 225m to Pounds 230m,
which had been expected.
There was uncertainty surrounding Lilley, the Glasgow-based construction
group, where a large placing of shares was said to have been attempted. BZW
was said to have tried to place more than 11m shares in Lilley, at a price
of 48 1/2 p, representing the holdings of a number of directors and
shareholders of Hatfield Estates, taken over by Lilley just over a year ago.
At the time of the takeover Hatfield directors agreed not to sell their
newly acquired Lilley shares for at least a year and not until Lilley's 1990
figures had been published.
Seaq turnover for Lilley was 365,000 shares, indicating that no placing had
taken place. Lilley settled 1 1/2 off at 47 1/2 p.
YJ Lovell's Pounds 30m rights issue, a two-for-five at 130p, received the
thumbs down by the market and Lovell shares dropped 33 to 145p.
MJ Gleeson advanced 17 to 805p following good results, with profits up 10
per cent at Pounds 5.05m, but Steetley was the latest building stock to
suffer from market fears that a rights issue could be forthcoming and fell
15 to 358p.
A report that UK groups were among the 26 first-tier contractors for
development of the F-22 Advanced Tactical Fighter project, America's next
generation of jet aircraft, sustained their respective share prices.
Details of the exact involvement should be released by the US Air Force next
week, but Dowty, 2 harder at 184p, hopes to receive a contract for Dollars
20m and Williams Holdings, also firmer at 284p, could be awarded a similar
amount. Williams was also the subject of a positive note from Smith New
Court.
Trafalgar House was bolstered by a broker's buy recommendation and settled 5
higher at 246p. The interim results are due on May 8.
With the company effectively dousing Wednesday's speculation of an impending
rights issue, ECC recouped much of that day's fall to close 10 higher at
420p. Pilkington firmed to 191p following news of a Pounds 7.4m disposal.
Fresh criticism of the fund-raising proposed by Cannon Street Investments
lowered the stock 7 more to 105p.
Vickers weakened further as fears of a sharp fall in sales of luxury cars
were confirmed by chairman Sir David Plastow. He warned at yesterday's
annual meeting that this, coupled with redundancy costs taken wholly in the
first half, would mean lower profits for the group. 'Over the full year
Rolls-Royce Motor Cars is unlikely to make a significant contribution to
Vickers' earnings,' he said. Vickers dipped to 205p before ending 2 easier
at 209p.
Automotive component stocks bowed to more bad news from the motor industry.
Hard on the heels of the Volvo job losses, news of which lowered Lex Service
8 more to 189p, speculation arose of the possible temporary closure of the
Ford plants at Dagenham and Halewood. This was denied but main suppliers GKN
and Lucas Industries still lost ground, the former closing 9 down at 364p
and the latter 5 off at 156p.
Tace fell 12 to 144p following the resignation of a director and of the
company's brokers, Hoare Govett. The latter was appointed less than a month
ago ahead of an anticipated capital restructuring.
Shell strengthened to close 7 up at 527p, responding to a spate of buy
recommendations in the US. Ultramar, which has substantial Canadian
businesses, was hurt by poor results from Imperial Oil, the Canadian unit of
Exxon, and settled 10 off at 319p with some big selling orders said to have
been in the market.
British Gas eased to 248p ahead of next Tuesday's deadline for its response
to the Ofgas proposals on domestic tariffs. If Gas fails to respond, Ofgas
will send its recommendations to the Monopolies Commission.
Carlton Communications climbed 11 to 559p as Hoare Govett recommended the
stock for the long term. Analysts were impressed with the company's new
products at a television equipment exhibition in the US. The broker,
however, remained cautious in the short term, trimming this year's profits
forecast by Pounds 7m to Pounds 103m.
The return of rights issue talk concerning Granada left the shares 5 off at
187p.
Tour operator Airtours jumped 44 to 443p, the day after the company took a
group of analysts to the Champagne district of France for a presentation.
Sentiment was also helped by the arrival of the company as a constituent of
the FT-A All-share index - tracking funds are now likely to buy the stock.
New issue Headline Book Publishing closed at 122p, compared with a placing
price of 100p.
Lancashire &amp; London Investment Trust advanced 9 to 103p on the Pounds 8.4m
offer from fellow trust and main shareholder Anglo Scandinavian Investment
Trust.
National Home Loans reflected investor uncertainty ahead of today's interim
results with a loss of 5 at 134p.
