FT  26 APR 91 / International Company News: Data General extends 'open
systems' products
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DATA GENERAL, buoyed by its first quarterly profit in five years, now aims
to re-establish itself as a leader in the field of mid-range computers,
writes Louise Kehoe. With the introduction of a new range of high
performance computers yesterday, the company claimed that it is on the way
to achieving long-term profitability.
Data General's comeback strategy is to focus on a new range of 'open
systems' products, based on industry standards, while also boosting sales of
its established proprietary products.
The new systems, launched at international events, extend the performance of
Data General's open systems product line into the realms of the mainframe
computer.
The new Aviion systems are based on Reduced Instruction Set Computer (RISC)
microprocessors supplied by Motorola and will process 117m instructions per
second, supporting up to 1,275 users on a network, the company said. Prices
start at Dollars 96,000.
Industry analysts predicted that the new products will significantly boost
Data General's Open Systems sales, which stood at about Dollars 100m last
year when the company had total revenues of Dollars 1.22bn.
Data General earned Dollars 12.4m in its last fiscal quarter, on revenue of
Dollars 311.7m. For it fiscal 1990, the company lost Dollars 139.8m on
revenue of Dollars 1.22bn.
Earlier this week, Data General announced the sale of its Japanese unit
Nippon Data General, to Omron of Kyoto, Japan,for about Dollars 46m. The
company expects to report a gain from the sale of Dollars 13m.
