<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / International Company News: TWA's London route sales cleared
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AVIATION authorities in the US yesterday gave Trans World Airlines, the
heavily-indebted US carrier, permission to sell three of its London Heathrow
route authorities to American Airlines, the larger and stronger US carrier.
But it said TWA would be required to retain routes between three other US
cities - Baltimore, Philadelphia, and St Louis - and London. The ailing
airline, owned by Mr Carl Icahn, the US corporate raider, originally planned
to sell the six routes, plus other assets to American, for Dollars 445m in
mid-December.
Since then, the sale has proved controversial. Some observers - including
TWA's unions - have claimed that, shorn of these routes, TWA would not be a
viable operating entity in the long-term.
The picture was muddied further when Mr Kirk Kerkorian, the wealthy West
Coast investor, said he was interested in buying TWA, but only if it kept
the London routes.
Mr Samuel Skinner said it had been 'amongst the most difficult decisions'
since becoming US Transportation Secretary two years ago. He claimed that
allowing the three routes between New York, Boston and Los Angeles to pass
to American would make the carrier 'a major player in the US-UK aviation
market'. United, American's biggest domestic rival, has already won access
to Heathrow by acquiring Pan Am's London routes.
Mr Skinner added that he was 'sympathetic' to the effort by unions and
government officials to protect the future of TWA'. But he ruled that Mr
Kerkorian's proposal did not 'compel disapproval of the entire transaction'.
He also claimed Mr Kerkorian was still free to negotiate with TWA, while
American and TWA drew up a new sale contract.
Last night, Mr Kerkorian's Tracinda Corporation said it 'remained committed
to a possible acquisition of TWA', although there were still 'substantial
unanswered questions regarding the status of the American/TWA contract'.
Mr Icahn suggested that that covered the sale of 'six routes or fewer than
six routes. . . for a total purchase price of Dollars 445m', while American
said the contract barred discussions between TWA and Mr Kerkorian.
American declined to clarify whether, by retaining the existing contract, it
might have to pay Dollars 445m for three routes.
</TEXT>
