FT  26 APR 91 / Moscow set to play key role in Middle East peace talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SOVIET UNION is poised to play a key role in the search for a Middle
East peace settlement, Mr Alexander Bessmertnykh, the country's foreign
minister said yesterday.
After four hours of talks with Mr James Baker, US secretary of state, in the
Caucasian town of Kislovodsk, Mr Bessmertnykh said Moscow would give a
'positive response' to the US proposal that it co-sponsor a Middle East
peace conference.
'The Soviet Union and the US intend to assist in the convening and holding
of a peace conference . . . We intend to act as sponsors,' he said at a news
conference.
His announcement came as the official news agency Tass reported that he
planned to visit Israel in May - a move which could lead to the renewal of
full diplomatic relations. Links were cut by Moscow during the 1967 Six Day
War.
Mr Bessmertnykh said the itinerary and exact date of his visit were being
worked out. 'Our relations with Israel are developing, and if this tendency
continues, there will be no difficulties in establishing full diplomatic
relations.'
Israeli officials, who have said that Moscow cannot take part in the
proposed conference without the restoration of full relations, said they had
received no prior notice of Mr Bessmertnykh's visit. But they said it would
be a welcome step towards restoring ties.
Moscow is understood to be ready to renew full links.
On regional peace, the Soviet minister laid out a three-stage negotiating
process:
The holding of a regional peace conference.
Separate discussions with the Palestinians - although it is not clear which
other countries would be at the talks.
A 'representative international peace conference' in which both regional and
world powers would participate.
Mr Baker, who arrived in Israel last night for his second round of talks
there in a week, said after the meeting with Mr Bessmertnykh that there was
a better chance than before of achieving a settlement in the region,
although he said that there were still 'considerable obstacles'.
Israel has made it clear from the start it does not oppose Soviet
co-sponsorship of a proposed regional peace conference. However, officials
said the government would continue to resist other features sought by Mr
Baker, who is scheduled to hold talks in Jerusalem today.
The two sides are at loggerheads over continued expansion of Jewish
settlement in the occupied territories.
Mr Bessmertnykh also predicted that a compromise on the conventional forces
in Europe treaty, signed last November but not ratified, was emerging.
</TEXT>
