<DOCNO>FT911-2949</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AGFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Rail unions fail to agree response to
pay offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS OF rail unions yesterday failed to agree on whether to ballot on
industrial action or seek arbitration over a pay offer of 7 per cent from
British Rail. They will try to establish a common strategy within a week.
The executives of the RMT and Aslef rail unions will meet separately to
discuss whether to hold an industrial-action ballot of up to 95,000 BR
workers over a pay offer which BR says is final and both unions have
rejected.
Mr Derrick Fullick, Aslef general secretary, said after the meeting of the
federation of rail unions that the unions' executives would discuss whether
to ballot or seek arbitration through the Railway Staffs National Tribunal.
Aslef leaders have favoured arbitration because they are negotiating with BR
on new arbitration machinery and do not want to be seen to break the
established mechanism under which all pay disputes should be resolved
through the RSNT.
The RMT is more sceptical about arbitration and some on its executive favour
an industrial action ballot to test support for strikes similar to the
campaign of industrial action in 1989.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, RMT general secretary, said BR had 'cynically manipulated'
negotiations by delaying talks until the inflation rate had fallen. The
unions would consider all options to force an improvement.
The two unions will also try to reach a unified position with the TSSA
white-collar union, whose leaders will consider the BR offer next week.
The meeting in London between the RMT and Aslef came as the Union of
Communication Workers separately decided to ballot 14,500 counter and
clerical staff in the Post Office on industrial action over a 6.8 per cent
pay offer.
Mr Alan Tuffin, UCW general secretary, said he could not recommend the
'inadequate' offer.
</TEXT>
